**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**
Vision-language models (VLMs) have shown significant progress in zero-shot classification tasks but struggle when the data distribution of downstream datasets differs from the pre-training distribution. There is a need for more effective adaptation frameworks and improved evaluation metrics to address these challenges. Leveraging audio-visual cues can further enhance the robustness and performance of VLMs.

**Here are the five core questions:**

**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**
How can we develop a more effective adaptation framework for vision-language models that leverages audio-visual cues to handle zero-shot classification tasks with distributional shifts?

**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**
Solving this problem will significantly improve the robustness and applicability of vision-language models in real-world scenarios where data distribution shifts are common. By integrating audio-visual cues, we can enhance the models' ability to understand and interact with the world, leading to more accurate and reliable zero-shot performance. This research will advance the field of machine learning by providing scalable solutions that can be readily implemented in various applications.

**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**
The challenge lies in designing a framework that can effectively capture and adapt to distributional shifts while maintaining high performance. Naive approaches may fail due to the complexity of the data and the need for sophisticated mechanisms to handle distributional differences. Integrating audio-visual cues adds another layer of complexity, requiring advanced techniques to synchronize and leverage both modalities.

**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**
Previous methods have focused on specific aspects of the problem, such as improving zero-shot performance or adapting to distributional shifts, but have not combined these elements in a comprehensive framework. Additionally, there is a lack of comprehensive evaluation metrics to guide the adaptation process. The integration of audio-visual cues has not been extensively explored in the context of vision-language model adaptation.

**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**
The proposed methodology will involve developing a new adaptation framework that combines the strengths of existing methods, such as CapS-Adapter and M-Adapter, with additional mechanisms to handle distributional shifts. We will integrate audio-visual cues using techniques like early fusion and contrastive learning to enhance the robustness of the models. We will design new evaluation metrics that consider both visual and audio cues to assess the similarity between support set images and the target data distribution. The framework will be evaluated on a diverse set of datasets, and the expected outcomes include improved zero-shot performance and robustness to distributional shifts.

### Next Task

The next task is to draft a detailed research proposal based on the refined '5q' and ensure that it aligns with your research goals and expertise in audio-visual learning and zero-shot learning. This proposal should include a literature review, methodology, expected results, and a discussion of the broader implications of the research.
